ming schools to improve their systems/curriculum/staff qualifications, etc.  or force to shut down for low enrollment.  More resources will go to the schools with proven track records.  These school can expand and continue their superior approach to education.  Competition will sharpen our our educational system.  Now, if you live in a &quot;crappy&quot; area, yu either move to an area with a better school district, or stay put and send your kid to the best school you can afford. Sending my kid to the neighborhood crappy public school and demanding they change their ways isn't going to loosen the grip of the teacher unions nor have any measureable profound impact on the quality of the public school system in an acceptable timeframe. Don't use my  kid as a social experiment.  Fix the public schools, then maybe I'll quit my 2nd job and trust them enough to educate my child. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1182" language="en" documentId="4313" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="JJ4214" date="Aug 29, 2013 5:25PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="9" thumbsDown="0" origId="4313" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1182"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>